00:00:15,640 --> 00:00:21,080
This quarter, we're going to learn about field theory, classical field theory.

4
00:00:21,080 --> 00:00:34,220
Fields such as the electromagnetic field, gravitational field, other fields in nature,

5
00:00:34,220 --> 00:00:42,400
which I won't name right now, propagate, which means they change according to rules

6
00:00:42,400 --> 00:00:45,780
which give them a wave-like character moving through space.

7
00:00:47,680 --> 00:00:49,860
And one of the fundamental principles

8
00:00:49,860 --> 00:00:51,060
of the classical field theory is that it's a field that is a wave-like character.

9
00:00:51,060 --> 00:00:56,040
One of the fundamental principles of field theory, in fact, more broadly,

10
00:00:57,120 --> 00:01:02,220
nature in general, is the principle of relativity.

11
00:01:03,200 --> 00:01:08,580
The principle of special relativity in this particular case.

12
00:01:10,200 --> 00:01:15,100
The principle of special relativity, well, let's just call it the principle of relativity,

13
00:01:15,820 --> 00:01:17,000
goes way back.

14
00:01:17,000 --> 00:01:20,200
There was not an invention of Einstein's.

15
00:01:21,060 --> 00:01:21,960
There was not an invention of Einstein's.

16
00:01:21,960 --> 00:01:28,880
I'm not absolutely sure when it was first announced or articulated in the form which I'll spell it out.

17
00:01:28,880 --> 00:01:33,860
I don't know whether it was Galileo or Newton or those who came after them,

18
00:01:34,340 --> 00:01:38,460
but those early pioneers certainly had the right idea.

19
00:01:43,020 --> 00:01:45,980
It begins with the idea of an inertial reference frame.

20
00:01:45,980 --> 00:01:50,160
Now, an inertial reference frame, this is something a bit tautological.

21
00:01:51,060 --> 00:01:53,060
It's an inertial reference frame.

22
00:01:53,060 --> 00:01:59,060
Newton's equations, F equals m a, are satisfied in an inertial reference frame.

23
00:01:59,060 --> 00:02:01,060
What is an inertial reference frame?

24
00:02:01,060 --> 00:02:05,060
It's a frame of reference in which Newton's equations are satisfied.

25
00:02:05,060 --> 00:02:12,060
I'm not going to explain any further what an inertial reference frame is,

26
00:02:12,060 --> 00:02:18,060
except to say that the idea of an inertial reference frame is by no means unique.

27
00:02:18,060 --> 00:02:20,860
A reference frame, first of all, what is a reference frame?

28
00:02:20,860 --> 00:02:22,860
What does a reference frame entail?

29
00:02:22,860 --> 00:02:27,860
A reference frame, first of all, entails a set of coordinate axes in ordinary space,

30
00:02:28,860 --> 00:02:32,860
x, y, and z, and you know how to think about those.

31
00:02:32,860 --> 00:02:40,860
But it also entails the idea that the coordinate system may be moving or not moving,

32
00:02:40,860 --> 00:02:44,860
relative to whom, relative to whomever.

33
00:02:44,860 --> 00:02:50,860
We sitting here, or you sitting here in this classroom here, define a frame of reference.

34
00:02:50,860 --> 00:02:54,860
We can pick the vertical direction to be the z-axis,

35
00:02:54,860 --> 00:02:58,860
the horizontal direction along my arms here to be the x-axis,

36
00:02:58,860 --> 00:03:02,860
x plus that way, x is minus in that direction.

37
00:03:02,860 --> 00:03:04,860
And which one have I left out?

38
00:03:04,860 --> 00:03:10,860
I have left out the y-axis, which points toward you from me.

39
00:03:10,860 --> 00:03:16,860
So there are some coordinate axes for space, x, y, and z,

40
00:03:16,860 --> 00:03:18,860
and in addition to specify a...

41
00:03:20,860 --> 00:03:27,040
frame of reference, one also imagines that this entire

42
00:03:27,820 --> 00:03:34,300
coordinate system is moving in some way relative to you sitting there

43
00:03:34,300 --> 00:03:38,860
presumably with a uniform velocity in a definite direction

44
00:03:39,680 --> 00:03:43,580
If your frame of reference is an inertial frame of reference

45
00:03:43,580 --> 00:03:50,420
in other words, if when you throw balls around or juggle or do whatever you're supposed to do in an inertial frame of reference

46
00:03:50,420 --> 00:03:53,620
if you find yourself in an inertial frame of reference

47
00:03:53,620 --> 00:04:01,080
then every other frame of reference that's moving with uniform velocity relative to you

48
00:04:01,080 --> 00:04:03,340
now remember what uniform velocity means

49
00:04:03,340 --> 00:04:06,340
it doesn't just mean with uniform speed

50
00:04:06,340 --> 00:04:10,620
it means with uniform speed in an unchanging direction

51
00:04:10,620 --> 00:04:13,860
such a frame of reference is also inertial

52
00:04:13,860 --> 00:04:15,860
if it's accelerated

53
00:04:15,860 --> 00:04:20,400
if it starts standing still and then suddenly picks up some speed

54
00:04:20,400 --> 00:04:23,400
then it's not an inertial frame of reference

55
00:04:23,400 --> 00:04:28,900
all inertial frames of reference according to Newton

56
00:04:28,900 --> 00:04:32,900
and also I think also Galileo

57
00:04:32,900 --> 00:04:38,900
Galileo was often credited with the idea but I never read enough of Galileo to know whether he actually had it or not

58
00:04:38,900 --> 00:04:43,900
neither did I read enough of Newton

59
00:04:43,900 --> 00:04:48,900
they both wrote in languages that I don't understand

60
00:04:50,400 --> 00:04:54,900
what was I saying?

61
00:04:54,900 --> 00:04:56,900
oh yes

62
00:04:56,900 --> 00:04:57,900
right

63
00:04:57,900 --> 00:05:02,900
according to both Newton and anybody else who thought about it very hard

64
00:05:02,900 --> 00:05:08,900
the laws of physics are the same in all inertial reference frames

65
00:05:08,900 --> 00:05:12,900
laws of physics meaning F equals ma

66
00:05:12,900 --> 00:05:15,400
the forces between objects

67
00:05:15,400 --> 00:05:20,400
all the things that we would normally call laws of nature or laws of physics

68
00:05:20,400 --> 00:05:24,400
don't distinguish between one frame of reference and another

69
00:05:24,400 --> 00:05:33,400
if you want a kind of pictorial example that I like to use a lot when I'm explaining this to children

70
00:05:33,400 --> 00:05:35,400
or to grown-ups

71
00:05:35,400 --> 00:05:37,900
I like to think about the laws of juggling

72
00:05:37,900 --> 00:05:43,400
there are very definite procedures that you train your body to do

73
00:05:43,400 --> 00:05:47,400
in order to be able to juggle balls correctly

74
00:05:47,400 --> 00:05:50,400
now you can imagine yourself being

75
00:05:50,400 --> 00:05:52,400
in a railroad car

76
00:05:52,400 --> 00:05:55,400
moving with perfectly uniform velocity

77
00:05:55,400 --> 00:05:57,400
down the x-axis

78
00:05:57,400 --> 00:05:59,400
and trying to juggle

79
00:05:59,400 --> 00:06:03,400
do you have to compensate for the fact that the train is moving?

80
00:06:03,400 --> 00:06:11,400
in particular when you throw a ball up into the air do you have to reach over to the right to compensate for the fact that the train is moving to the left?

81
00:06:11,400 --> 00:06:12,400
my left, your right?

82
00:06:12,400 --> 00:06:14,400
the answer is no

83
00:06:14,400 --> 00:06:15,400
you don't

84
00:06:15,400 --> 00:06:19,400
the laws of juggling are the same in every reference frame

85
00:06:19,400 --> 00:06:21,400
in every inertial reference frame

86
00:06:21,400 --> 00:06:25,400
whatever you do in one reference frame you do exactly the same thing

87
00:06:25,400 --> 00:06:30,400
and you'll succeed or fail depending on whether you're a good juggler or not

88
00:06:30,400 --> 00:06:35,400
but it will not depend on whether you're moving with uniform velocity

89
00:06:35,400 --> 00:06:39,400
so the laws of juggling are the same in every inertial reference frame

90
00:06:39,400 --> 00:06:44,400
the laws of mechanics are the same in every inertial reference frame

91
00:06:44,400 --> 00:06:48,400
the laws, Newtonian laws of gravity are the same in every inertial frame

92
00:06:48,400 --> 00:06:50,400
according to Newton

93
00:06:52,400 --> 00:06:56,400
what about the laws of electrical phenomena?

94
00:06:56,400 --> 00:07:00,400
well, there, there was a clash

95
00:07:00,400 --> 00:07:05,400
the clash had to do with Maxwell's equations

96
00:07:05,400 --> 00:07:09,400
Maxwell's equations were the field equations, the field theory

97
00:07:09,400 --> 00:07:12,400
that governed the electromagnetic field

98
00:07:12,400 --> 00:07:15,400
and the way that it propagated and sent waves

99
00:07:15,400 --> 00:07:17,400
electromagnetic waves

100
00:07:17,400 --> 00:07:19,400
that we ordinarily call light

101
00:07:19,400 --> 00:07:21,400
or radio waves or so forth

102
00:07:21,400 --> 00:07:25,400
and the fundamental dilemma, as you all know, I'm sure you all know

103
00:07:25,400 --> 00:07:31,400
the fundamental dilemma was both according to, well, here was the dilemma

104
00:07:31,400 --> 00:07:38,400
Maxwell's equations said light moves with a certain velocity

105
00:07:38,400 --> 00:07:42,400
if you take the various constants that appear in Maxwell's equations

106
00:07:42,400 --> 00:07:44,400
and put them together in the right way

107
00:07:44,400 --> 00:07:47,400
you get the velocity of waves moving with a certain velocity

108
00:07:47,400 --> 00:07:49,400
moving down an axis

109
00:07:49,400 --> 00:07:54,400
and that velocity comes out to be a certain number out of Maxwell's equations

110
00:07:54,400 --> 00:07:56,400
you have two choices

111
00:07:56,400 --> 00:08:01,400
one is to believe that Maxwell's equations are true laws of nature

112
00:08:01,400 --> 00:08:04,400
as good as any other laws of nature

113
00:08:04,400 --> 00:08:10,400
in which case the principle of relativity says they should be the same in every reference frame

114
00:08:10,400 --> 00:08:15,400
but if it follows from Maxwell's equations that the speed of light is

115
00:08:15,400 --> 00:08:19,400
three times ten to the eighth meters per second

116
00:08:19,400 --> 00:08:21,400
which is about what it is

117
00:08:21,400 --> 00:08:24,400
if it follows from Maxwell's equations that light moves that fast

118
00:08:24,400 --> 00:08:29,400
and if Maxwell's equations are laws of physics, fundamental laws of physics

119
00:08:29,400 --> 00:08:33,400
and if the laws of physics are the same in every reference frame

120
00:08:33,400 --> 00:08:37,400
then the speed of light must be the same in every reference frame

121
00:08:37,400 --> 00:08:40,400
but that was very hard to swallow

122
00:08:40,400 --> 00:08:43,400
because if a light beam is going down that axis

123
00:08:43,400 --> 00:08:45,400
and you chase it and run along with it

124
00:08:45,400 --> 00:08:48,400
at let's say three quarters of the speed of light

125
00:08:48,400 --> 00:08:52,400
then you ought to see that light ray moving much more slowly

126
00:08:52,400 --> 00:08:56,400
than three times ten to the eighth meters per second relative to you

127
00:08:56,400 --> 00:08:59,400
on the other hand, a light ray going in the other direction

128
00:08:59,400 --> 00:09:01,400
since you're sort of running into it

129
00:09:01,400 --> 00:09:04,400
you should see going even faster

130
00:09:04,400 --> 00:09:09,400
so all these possibilities could not simultaneously be correct

131
00:09:09,400 --> 00:09:13,400
that the laws of nature are the same in every reference frame

132
00:09:13,400 --> 00:09:15,400
and that Maxwell's equations

133
00:09:15,400 --> 00:09:17,400
are laws of physics

134
00:09:17,400 --> 00:09:20,400
in the same sense that Newton's laws of physics

135
00:09:20,400 --> 00:09:22,400
namely the same in every reference frame

136
00:09:22,400 --> 00:09:24,400
something had to give

137
00:09:24,400 --> 00:09:27,400
well, the point was of course

138
00:09:27,400 --> 00:09:29,400
that they were good laws of nature

139
00:09:29,400 --> 00:09:32,400
and that they were the same in every reference frame

140
00:09:32,400 --> 00:09:34,400
the thing that had to give

141
00:09:34,400 --> 00:09:37,400
is our concepts of velocity, space, and time

142
00:09:37,400 --> 00:09:39,400
and how we measure velocity

143
00:09:42,400 --> 00:09:45,400
especially velocities which are up near the surface

144
00:09:45,400 --> 00:09:47,400
near the speed of light

145
00:09:47,400 --> 00:09:50,400
now, I'm not going to spend the full amount of time

146
00:09:50,400 --> 00:09:54,400
that I did previously on the special theory of relativity

147
00:09:54,400 --> 00:09:58,400
that can be found on lectures from how long ago?

148
00:09:58,400 --> 00:10:00,400
they're on the internet I believe

149
00:10:00,400 --> 00:10:02,400
relativity and electromagnetism

150
00:10:02,400 --> 00:10:04,400
I think that was maybe about three quarters ago

151
00:10:04,400 --> 00:10:06,400
I've lost track

152
00:10:06,400 --> 00:10:09,400
yeah, they're up there, they're on the net

153
00:10:09,400 --> 00:10:11,400
and they're the lectures on relativity

154
00:10:11,400 --> 00:10:14,400
special relativity and electromagnetic theory

155
00:10:15,400 --> 00:10:17,400
we're just going to cut through it real fast

156
00:10:17,400 --> 00:10:20,400
we're going to cut through the basic ideas of relativity

157
00:10:20,400 --> 00:10:22,400
a little more mathematically

158
00:10:22,400 --> 00:10:25,400
than I would do if I were teaching it for the first time

159
00:10:25,400 --> 00:10:27,400
if I teach it the first time

160
00:10:27,400 --> 00:10:29,400
I tend to teach it the way

161
00:10:29,400 --> 00:10:31,400
Einstein first conceived of it

162
00:10:31,400 --> 00:10:33,400
how do you measure distances?

163
00:10:33,400 --> 00:10:35,400
how do you measure velocities?

164
00:10:35,400 --> 00:10:39,400
how does the propagation of light influence these things?

165
00:10:39,400 --> 00:10:42,400
instead I'm going to take a more mathematical view of it

166
00:10:42,400 --> 00:10:45,400
and think about the properties of light

167
00:10:45,400 --> 00:10:51,400
and the properties of various kinds of coordinate transformations

168
00:10:51,400 --> 00:10:55,400
coordinates now consist not only of x, y, and z

169
00:10:55,400 --> 00:10:58,400
but also time, t

170
00:10:58,400 --> 00:11:02,400
so imagine every event in the world

171
00:11:02,400 --> 00:11:04,400
is characterized by

172
00:11:04,400 --> 00:11:06,400
just like every particle

173
00:11:06,400 --> 00:11:09,400
would be characterized by a position

174
00:11:09,400 --> 00:11:11,400
x, y, and z

175
00:11:11,400 --> 00:11:14,400
every event taking place in space-time

176
00:11:14,400 --> 00:11:16,400
is characterized by four coordinates

177
00:11:16,400 --> 00:11:18,400
x, y, z, and t

